childnodes.sy: A combination market and restaurant in the International District, Ping’s serves some of the best dumplings in Seattle. The soup dumplings and pork and chive dumplings are standouts, but do yourself a favor and take the proprietress’ advice.
King Noodle’s congee — a type of rice porridge — makes the ultimate cold weather comfort food. Order some Chinese donuts for dipping if you really want to treat yourself.

The beef brisket wonton noodle bowl, Chinese broccoli and Chinese donuts are must-order items at Mike’s Noodle House. It’s always packed, so allow time to park and wait for a table, and bring cash because they don’t take credit cards.
Morning, noon or night, Honey Court serves up great seafood, dim sum and more. Pork and shrimp wonton soup makes a delicious late-night snack.

Hue Ky Mi Gia cooks great rice noodle dishes in the International District. They’re all about options here: all noodles can be ordered either dry or as a soup, and the pan-fried chicken wings are amazing, too.
There’s nothing like a steaming bowl of pho to warm and fill your belly on a cold day, and Green Leaf’s other dishes — like the omelet with pan-fried tofu — are delicious and hearty as well.

Gourmet Noodle Bowl serves up hearty portions of its noodles, soups and dumplings, so be prepared to share. Start off with flavorful appetizers like the Taiwanese pork bun with peanut topping and Shanghai-style steamed dumplings.

There’s always a huge line for the banh mi at Saigon Deli, and for good reason. Double ham, barbecue ham, spring roll –  it’s all incredible. Food is take-away only, so settle in at a nearby park to enjoy your sandwiches.
